from the British Isles to the Southern Hemisphere in the 19th century. These varieties are similar to one another, not because of historical connections between them, but because they were formed out of similar mixtures according to the same principles. A key argument is that social factors such as social status, prestige and stigma played no role in the early years of colonial dialect development, and that the ‘work’ of colonial new-dialect formation was carried out by children over a period of two generations. The book also uses insights derived from the study of early forms of these colonial dialects to shed light back on the nature of 19th-century English in the British Isles.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aEnglish languagexColonieszGreat Britain. 0aEnglish languagexCommonwealth countries. 0aEnglish languagexDialectsxColonieszGreat Britain. 0aEnglish languagexDialectsxCommonwealth countries. 0aEnglish languagexDialectsxGreat BritainxColonies. 0aEnglish languagexDialectszCommonwealth countries. 0aEnglish languagexDialectszGreat BritainzColonies. 0aEnglish languagexGreat BritainxColonies. 0aEnglish languagexHistoryx19th century. 0aEnglish languagexVariationxColonieszGreat Britain. 0aEnglish languagexVariationxCommonwealth countries. 0aEnglish languagexVariationxGreat BritainxColonies. 0aEnglish languagexVariationzCommonwealth countries. 0aEnglish languagexVariationzGreat BritainzColonies. 0aEnglish languagey19th centuryxHistory. 0aEnglish languagezCommonwealth countries. 0aEnglish languagezGreat BritainzColonies. 0aLanguages in contactxColonieszGreat Britain. 0aLanguages in contactxCommonwealth countries. 0aLanguages in contactxGreat BritainxColonies. 0aLanguages in contactzCommonwealth countries. 0aLanguages in contactzGreat Brita